Beekeeping Stressors

The species of bees that beekeepers use are not native to the United States, and typically has origins from Europe. These species include the:

  • Italian Honey Bee - Most popular choice due to their high production of honey, wax, and brood (bee eggs), gentleness, and disease resistance
  • European Honey Bee - Common choice for beekeeping, decent honey, wax, and brood production, and able to withstand cold weather
  • Carniolan Honey Bee - Gentle, can withstand long winters, repopulates quickly in the Spring
  • Caucasian Honey Bee - Strong colonies, gentle, reaches max production of honey, wax, and brood in the summer

Beekeeping often use species that produce honey and beeswax as well as pollinate crops. Bees have a yearly cycle

After the summer season has passed, colonies prepare for the fall and winter seasons by stocking up on nectar and honey. The queen bee start to lay less eggs which will grow into "winter" worker bees that are physiologically fit to survive winter, and by the time the winter season starts the queen will stop laying eggs for the season. In the winter, there are less bees

Honey bees are important to US agriculture. Based on the NASS (National Agricultural Statistic Service), the reported number of bee colonies in 2021 was 2.92 million. (https://www.nass.usda.gov/Statistics_by_State/Regional_Office/Southern/includes/Publications/Livestock_Releases/Bee_and_Honey/2021/BEECOL2021.pdf)

The beekeeping industry includes hobbyists, part-timers, and commercial beekeepers. According to agmrc.org:

"Hobby-sized operations are those with 25 colonies or less, hobbyists with less than 5 colonies are not included in the colonies reported by the USDA. Part-timers are those with 25 to 300 colonies, and commercial operations are those with over 300 colonies. Hobbyists and part-timers account for roughly 40 percent of the honey production, and 1,600 commercial beekeepers are responsible for the remaining 60 percent of production."
This project aims to examine the leading stressors that lead to bee colony losses in different regions in the U.S.

Exploring the Bee Colony Dataset¶

Since the goal is to identify the the most influential stressors on bee colonies, it is necessary to first identify if the bee colonies are experiencing a noticable loss in their colony populations. I chose to use the percent loss column since its more standardized compared to the lost colonies column, since each colonies are different sizes the number of lost colonies may differ in magnitude.

Seeing the dataset so cluttered, I decided to plot the states' percent loss based on map region. Where:

West: California, Nevada, Utah, Colorado, Wyoming, Idaho, Montana, Washington, Oregon, Alaska

Northeast: Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, Vermont, New Hampshire, Maine, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, New York

South: Louisiana, Arkansas, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Florida, South Carolina, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, Delaware

Midwest: North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, Missouri, Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio

Southwest: Arizona, New Mexico, Texas, Oklahoma

While going through the points there exists an "Other" state, the "Other" will be dropped. The U.S. is also listed as a state but it will not be included in any of the regional datasets, as it is unknown whether its the average of all states' data for each quarter or some other data related to the U.S.

Now that the bee colony data is more readable, taking a look at the means of each region's mean percent loss over the years shows that the Southwest region has the highest average percent loss of bee colonies of 13%. The region with the least average percent loss is the Northeast region at 9%. Based on the graphs it seems that there's a correlation between the season of the year and average percent loss. To further examine a possible relationship, the data corresponding to the spring and summer months as well as the fall and winter months must be grouped for each region.

On the violin plots the light blue portion plotted shows the distribution of each states' percent losses within a specific region. For the majority of the graphs with the exception of the Southwest Spring/Summer season, the distributions are right skewed, with more data leaning towards the lower end of the range rather than the higher end. For the Northeast, Midwest, and Southwest regions the range of the Fall/Winter season distributions almost doubles its range during the Spring/Summer seasons. Though based on the plotted means, only the Northeast and South regions had a significant jump in their percentage loss from the Spring/Summer seasons to Fall/Winter seasons, which could signify a correlation between the season and percentage loss.

HGTV Bee Edition: Bee Colony Renovation Data Exploration¶

Renovation includes requeening a surviving colony, which may help in increasing a colony's brood production, or a large transfer of honey bees into a colony either by nuc or package. A nuc, also known as a split or a nucleus colony, is typically a pre-established hive frame containing a queen, bees, honey, brood, and pollen. While a package only has bees and a queen. Both types are usually installed during the spring and they are helpful in boosting a weak colony's resources in the long run.

It's Hard to Be a Bee: Bee Stressor Dataset Exploration¶

In addition to their winter survival, imported bee species face a variety of different stressors. Including pesticides, pests such as hive beetles and varroa mites, environmental stress, diseases, and even a phenomenon called colony collapse disorder. This section aims to identify the major stressors for bee colonies from each U.S. region from 2015-2021.

Looking at the graph and summary statistics, all of the regions have varroa mites as their primary stressor over a period of 6 years. Ranging from 10% to 49% over all regions. With the Southern regions having the highest average percentage of varroa mites of 32%. Interestingly enough the varroa mites percentage in the Southwest, Midwest, and South have increased their winter seasons presence each year from 2015-2018. In all the regions except for the South region, the presence of hive beetles reached a new minimum during the winter of 2018 or 2019. Another interesting insight is that the South region has higher pests/parasites percentages than any other U.S. region.

Now lets see if there's a correlation between the varroa mites and colony loss. If there is a correlation, we would expect to see that the periods of times where the varroa mites population is higher, the percentage in colony loss is higher as well.
